WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:19.080
All About South Africa, by Philippa Tracey Copyright, Burlington Books 2013, All Rights

00:19.080 --> 00:31.760
Reserved Chapter 1 The Rainbow Nation

00:31.760 --> 00:37.640
How's it? Asked the young man sitting with his friends in the pub.

00:37.640 --> 00:39.120
How's what?

00:39.120 --> 00:41.120
answered the stranger.

00:41.120 --> 00:44.320
I asked how you are, said the young man.

00:44.320 --> 00:46.920
That's how South Africans greet each other.

00:47.280 --> 00:50.280
You're obviously not from here.

00:50.280 --> 00:52.320
No replied the stranger.

00:52.320 --> 00:56.880
My name's John and I'm visiting Cape Town from the UK.

00:56.880 --> 00:59.800
Come and join us, offered the young man.

00:59.800 --> 01:02.760
These are my friends Samuel and Adam.

01:02.760 --> 01:06.000
By the way, I'm Pitt.

01:06.000 --> 01:10.800
Welcome to South Africa, the Rainbow Nation, said Adam.

01:10.800 --> 01:14.160
The Rainbow Nation, inquired John.

01:14.160 --> 01:17.440
How did South Africa get that name?

01:17.440 --> 01:21.800
From all the different cultural groups here, answered Samuel.

01:21.800 --> 01:29.160
Just look at us, Pitt is an Afrikana, I'm African and Adam is coloured.

01:29.160 --> 01:32.960
You know John, it's quite amazing, remarked Pitt.

01:32.960 --> 01:37.360
Twenty-five years ago, we couldn't have a beer together in public.

01:37.680 --> 01:39.960
Why not, asked John?

01:39.960 --> 01:45.520
Because in those days, Europeans weren't allowed to mix with non-Europeans, explained

01:45.520 --> 01:46.520
Pitt.

01:46.520 --> 01:49.000
It's a long story.

01:49.000 --> 01:52.880
I'd like to hear it if you've got the time, said John.

01:52.880 --> 01:58.400
OK, so sit down and I'll try to explain, said Samuel.

01:58.400 --> 02:04.960
Well, you see, the first people to live in South Africa were the koi koi and sand people.

02:05.040 --> 02:11.960
They lived a quiet, peaceful life as hunters and farmers until the Dutch arrived in 1652

02:11.960 --> 02:14.200
and everything changed.

02:14.200 --> 02:20.760
There was a lot of fighting between the Dutch farmers, the Boers and the indigenous people.

02:20.760 --> 02:24.920
Why did the Dutch people come to South Africa, asked John?

02:24.920 --> 02:30.840
They came with a Dutch explorer named Jan van Ribic, explained Pitt.

02:30.840 --> 02:36.320
At that time, traders were travelling from Europe to the far east to buy spices, but

02:36.320 --> 02:41.840
it was a long journey and many sailors died of scurvy because they didn't have fresh

02:41.840 --> 02:43.400
food.

02:43.400 --> 02:50.760
The Cape of Good Hope was the halfway point, so the Dutch East India Company, DEIC, which

02:50.760 --> 02:56.800
controlled trade to the east, sent van Ribic and his helpers to build a fort there as a

02:56.800 --> 02:58.960
kind of refreshment stop.

02:59.040 --> 03:04.400
Passing ships could stop and get fresh provisions and medical care on their journey.

03:04.400 --> 03:10.800
So, I understand the first settlers were Europeans, but then how did the coloureds get

03:10.800 --> 03:11.800
here?

03:11.800 --> 03:12.800
Asked John.

03:12.800 --> 03:16.040
I can explain that, said Adam.

03:16.040 --> 03:22.400
You see, van Ribic didn't have enough men to build the fort, so the DEIC imported slaves

03:22.400 --> 03:25.720
from Asia and Africa to help build it.

03:25.720 --> 03:30.040
When the fort was finished, some of these men stayed at the Cape.

03:30.040 --> 03:35.040
The coloureds today are the descendants of these settlers and their slaves.

03:35.040 --> 03:38.720
I see, but what about the British, asked John?

03:38.720 --> 03:41.280
When did they arrive in Africa?

03:41.280 --> 03:46.880
I think the British landed here in 1795, said Pitt.

03:46.880 --> 03:49.800
Did they have problems with the boar settlers?

03:49.800 --> 03:50.800
Asked John?

03:50.800 --> 03:53.280
Yes, answered Pitt.

03:53.280 --> 03:57.120
The British and the boars never agreed on anything.

03:57.120 --> 04:02.640
The British wanted to abolish slavery and the boars weren't happy about that, so they

04:02.640 --> 04:05.880
took their slaves and left the Cape Colony.

04:05.880 --> 04:11.520
They moved to other parts of the country and established their own two republics there,

04:11.520 --> 04:14.200
the Orange Free State and the Transvaal.

04:14.200 --> 04:20.840
But today South Africa is one country, so how did that happen, asked John?

04:20.840 --> 04:24.080
It took some time, Pitt explained.

04:24.080 --> 04:29.560
Gold was discovered in the Transvaal and the British wanted that gold, so they went to

04:29.560 --> 04:32.320
war in 1899.

04:32.320 --> 04:34.960
That was called the Anglo-Boar War.

04:34.960 --> 04:38.600
So who won the war, asked John?

04:38.600 --> 04:44.920
Well, the boars fought hard, but the British won in the end, answered Pitt.

04:44.920 --> 04:50.320
The British general, Lord Kitchener, put the boars' wives and children into concentration

04:50.320 --> 04:51.880
camps.

04:51.880 --> 04:59.680
More than 7,000 boar fighters lost their lives in battle, but almost 28,000 women and children

04:59.680 --> 05:05.320
died in the concentration camps as a result of poor food and lack of hygiene.

05:05.320 --> 05:09.320
That's terrible, remarked John.

05:09.320 --> 05:11.720
Yes, said Pitt.

05:11.720 --> 05:17.680
So the British took control of the two boar republics and united them with their own colonies,

05:17.680 --> 05:24.800
the Cape and Natal, to form one country, South Africa, in 1910.

05:24.800 --> 05:27.760
And was that the end of the boars, asked John?

05:27.760 --> 05:31.600
No, not at all, continued Samuel.

05:31.600 --> 05:38.680
Because in 1948, the boars, who are now called Afrikaners, came to power and began a system

05:38.680 --> 05:40.960
of apartheid.

05:40.960 --> 05:44.720
What was apartheid exactly, asked John?

05:44.720 --> 05:49.520
That was the system of forced segregation between the races in South Africa, explained

05:49.520 --> 05:50.760
Pitt.

05:50.760 --> 05:58.240
It lasted until 1994, when Nelson Mandela and the ANC, the African National Congress, came

05:58.240 --> 05:59.240
to power.

05:59.240 --> 06:02.680
"'A apartheid sounds terrible,' said John.

06:02.680 --> 06:05.280
"'How did it affect your lives?'

06:05.280 --> 06:12.160
"'Well, as I said, we couldn't sit here together like this under apartheid,' said Pitt.

06:12.160 --> 06:16.640
You can hear more about that from the great man himself,' suggested Samuel.

06:16.640 --> 06:21.080
"'I've got an excellent DVD about Nelson Mandela.

06:21.080 --> 06:23.680
You can borrow it, if you like.'

06:23.680 --> 06:25.720
"'Great,' said John.

06:25.720 --> 06:28.120
"'Cheers,' said Pitt and Samuel.

06:28.120 --> 06:31.920
"'Enjoy your stay in sunny South Africa,' said Adam.

06:31.920 --> 06:34.920
"'Chapter two, the Mandela years.'

06:34.920 --> 06:41.520
"'So let's watch this DVD on Mandela,' thought John, later that evening.

06:41.520 --> 06:45.440
He switched the TV on and a deep voice declared.

06:45.440 --> 06:48.240
"'Allow me to introduce myself.

06:48.240 --> 06:52.760
My name is Nelson Roly-Shla-Shla Mandela.

06:52.760 --> 06:59.880
I became president of South Africa in 1994, but my battle against racial discrimination

06:59.880 --> 07:02.680
started long before then.

07:02.680 --> 07:05.600
This is my story.

07:05.600 --> 07:11.280
For hundreds of years, the blacks of Africans didn't have any rights.

07:11.280 --> 07:19.840
So in 1912, all the African people united to form the African National Congress, ANC.

07:19.840 --> 07:26.720
At the time, South Africa was changing because of the discovery of gold and diamonds.

07:26.720 --> 07:29.200
The Europeans owned the mines.

07:29.200 --> 07:35.760
The Africans weren't allowed to own land, so they worked in the Europeans' mines and farms.

07:35.760 --> 07:40.320
They did the work, and the white men got rich.

07:40.320 --> 07:46.840
But things got much worse when the National Party came into power in 1948 and introduced

07:46.840 --> 07:51.040
apartheid, a system of racial segregation.

07:51.040 --> 07:54.440
Apartheid laws.

07:54.440 --> 08:02.240
All South Africans must register according to their race, white, Indian, colored, or black.

08:02.240 --> 08:05.920
Only whites can vote.

08:05.920 --> 08:11.520
Africans aren't permitted to marry a person of any other racial group.

08:11.520 --> 08:19.000
No sexual act may be committed between a European and a person of any other racial group.

08:19.000 --> 08:23.120
Each racial group must live in its own area.

08:23.120 --> 08:26.640
Blacks must live in the tribal homelands.

08:26.640 --> 08:32.520
All blacks must carry passbooks, identity cards, at all times.

08:32.520 --> 08:37.200
If not, they may be arrested and imprisoned.

08:37.200 --> 08:39.960
These laws were very humiliating.

08:39.960 --> 08:47.520
At the post office, in shops, or at a bus stop, I couldn't stand in the same line as a European.

08:47.520 --> 08:54.480
In the parks, there were separate benches and toilets for Europeans and non-Europeans.

08:54.480 --> 08:58.800
We were treated like dirt, and I was furious inside.

08:58.800 --> 09:04.880
I wanted to take action, so I founded the ANC Youth League together with my colleagues

09:04.880 --> 09:08.760
Walter Sisulu and Oliver Tembo.

09:08.760 --> 09:10.920
We fought for the rights of our people.

09:10.920 --> 09:14.920
Don't think the government didn't try to stop us.

09:14.920 --> 09:19.600
Many of our leaders were living under house arrest or were imprisoned, and I was one of

09:19.600 --> 09:20.600
them.

09:20.600 --> 09:24.600
Later, the ANC was made illegal.

09:24.600 --> 09:29.800
I remember meeting Walter and Oliver in secret to plan our attacks.

09:29.800 --> 09:38.320
Then, in 1963, I was arrested for sabotage and imprisoned on Robin Island, off the coast

09:38.320 --> 09:40.920
of Cape Town.

09:40.920 --> 09:45.800
For eighteen years, I slept in a five-meter square cell.

09:45.800 --> 09:49.440
My bed was a thin straw mat on the floor.

09:49.440 --> 09:55.400
The food rations were small, and the work in the limestone quarry was hard.

09:55.400 --> 10:01.520
I was only allowed one visitor and one letter every six months.

10:01.520 --> 10:08.800
Even worse, when my eldest son and my mother died, I wasn't permitted to attend their funerals.

10:08.800 --> 10:11.760
It broke my heart.

10:11.760 --> 10:19.080
In 1976, while I was in prison, something terrible happened in Soweto, a black township

10:19.080 --> 10:21.040
near Johannesburg.

10:21.040 --> 10:26.480
The black children were demonstrating because they didn't want to be taught in Afrikaans.

10:26.480 --> 10:30.880
It was a peaceful demonstration until the police arrived.

10:30.880 --> 10:36.680
The children started to sing their national anthem in their language, and then the police

10:36.680 --> 10:39.120
started to shoot.

10:39.120 --> 10:43.280
They killed a twelve-year-old boy called Hector Peterson.

10:43.280 --> 10:48.560
The next day, his picture was in every newspaper around the world.

10:48.560 --> 10:52.680
I felt terribly sorry for poor, innocent Hector.

10:52.680 --> 10:58.000
He was only one of hundreds of victims of violence.

10:58.000 --> 10:59.000
When P.W.

10:59.000 --> 11:05.440
Buerta became Prime Minister, he promised to change things, but he was determined to prevent

11:05.440 --> 11:08.080
black supremacy.

11:08.080 --> 11:13.680
During the eleven years he was Prime Minister, nothing changed for my people, and I was happy

11:13.680 --> 11:15.880
when he resigned.

11:15.880 --> 11:16.880
F.W.

11:16.880 --> 11:23.760
de Klerk replaced Buerta and filled me with hope, because his new policy was one man,

11:23.760 --> 11:25.240
one vote.

11:25.240 --> 11:30.880
He immediately made changes in the country, setting political prisoners, including ANC

11:30.880 --> 11:35.560
leaders, free, everyone except me.

11:35.560 --> 11:38.520
Then one day he sent for me.

11:38.520 --> 11:42.480
I was taken secretly into his office in Cape Town.

11:42.480 --> 11:47.480
We were alone, and we sat for a moment just looking at each other.

11:47.480 --> 11:53.120
It was our first meeting face-to-face, and I could tell he was impressed by my dignity

11:53.120 --> 11:55.240
and self-confidence.

11:55.240 --> 12:01.000
By the end of the meeting, we both knew we could do business together.

12:01.000 --> 12:07.040
Next time we meet, we'll discuss ending your imprisonment, he promised me.

12:07.040 --> 12:12.240
de Klerk worked on his new policy for one year and kept it a secret.

12:12.240 --> 12:18.840
Then, on the 2nd of February 1990, the day of revelation arrived.

12:18.840 --> 12:25.880
I was now living in a private home on the grounds of Victor Fester prison near Cape Town.

12:25.880 --> 12:30.760
There I sat, glued to the TV screen as de Klerk began his speech.

12:30.760 --> 12:33.760
I'll never forget that day.

12:33.760 --> 12:40.480
In one action, he announced the end of apartheid and changed South Africa immediately.

12:40.480 --> 12:45.560
The members of my party were free to carry our green, yellow and black flag, and nine

12:45.560 --> 12:53.960
days later, I, prisoner, 46664, was going to walk free.

12:53.960 --> 12:57.040
I couldn't believe it.

12:57.040 --> 13:04.440
On the 11th of February 1990, I was set free from prison after 27 years.

13:04.440 --> 13:11.040
The world was a different place, and it took me some time to adapt to my freedom.

13:11.040 --> 13:17.880
Four years later, the first democratic elections took place, and I became South Africa's first

13:17.880 --> 13:20.320
black president.

13:20.320 --> 13:28.520
My long walk to freedom was over, and my dream of a democratic South Africa was finally coming

13:28.520 --> 13:29.520
true.

13:29.520 --> 13:34.240
Chapter 3 People and Cultures of South Africa

13:34.240 --> 13:39.360
South Africa is home to over 48 million people.

13:39.360 --> 13:47.760
Almost 77% of the people are black or African, 11% are white and 9% are colored.

13:47.760 --> 13:52.680
All of mixed African, Asian and European descent.

13:52.680 --> 13:56.240
Just over half the population live in cities.

13:56.240 --> 14:02.600
Three-quarters of the population are Christian, and the rest are Hindus, Muslims, Jews, or

14:02.600 --> 14:05.280
people without a religion.

14:05.280 --> 14:12.360
The African people are from many different tribes, but most speak Zulu and Coza.

14:12.360 --> 14:19.080
There are 11 officially recognized languages, and most are indigenous to South Africa.

14:19.080 --> 14:25.520
With this mix of cultures and languages, you might wonder how people understand each other.

14:25.520 --> 14:29.920
English is widely spoken and understood by most people.

14:29.920 --> 14:35.520
English is the language of business, politics, tourism and the media.

14:35.520 --> 14:40.680
Road signs and official forms are always in English, and the president makes his speeches

14:40.680 --> 14:42.320
in English.

14:42.320 --> 14:46.880
It meets some of the different people who form the modern South Africa.

14:46.880 --> 14:48.480
How's it?

14:48.480 --> 14:53.920
My name is Emily, and English is my mother Tang, like many of the English speakers in South

14:53.920 --> 14:54.920
Africa.

14:54.920 --> 14:57.480
I live in a big city called Johannesburg.

14:57.480 --> 15:02.880
I'm of British descent, and I love eating fish and chops, but my culture is very different

15:02.880 --> 15:04.560
from the British one.

15:04.560 --> 15:08.960
I live in a beautiful home, and I've got maids who cook and clean.

15:08.960 --> 15:13.520
Some say we live in a golden cage because we must protect our homes against crime with

15:13.520 --> 15:17.600
barbed wire and electric gates.

15:17.600 --> 15:24.760
My name is Willem, and I'm one of about three million white Afrikaners in South Africa today.

15:24.760 --> 15:26.800
I speak Afrikanz.

15:26.800 --> 15:30.360
In Dutch, Afrikaner means African.

15:30.360 --> 15:35.600
Although our ancestors were Dutch, French and German settlers, we've got our own culture

15:35.600 --> 15:37.400
and language.

15:37.400 --> 15:42.640
Most of Afrikan's words come from Dutch, but the slaves and colonists also influenced

15:42.640 --> 15:44.320
it a lot.

15:44.320 --> 15:49.400
English words like apartheid, trek, and world beasts come from Afrikanz.

15:49.400 --> 15:53.600
My dad is a farmer from Paul, a town in the western Cape.

15:53.600 --> 15:58.000
Paul is well known because Nelson Mandela spent three years there at the Victor Verster

15:58.000 --> 15:59.800
prison.

15:59.800 --> 16:03.360
My name is Shaka, and I speak Zulu.

16:03.360 --> 16:08.120
I'm named after the great Zulu warrior, Shaka Zulu.

16:08.120 --> 16:12.920
I love singing and dancing, and I'm a great storyteller.

16:12.920 --> 16:16.840
The Zulu's are the largest African group in South Africa.

16:16.840 --> 16:22.160
We're part of the Inguni people, and our ancestors came from East Africa.

16:22.160 --> 16:26.040
We believe in ancestral spirits and magic.

16:26.040 --> 16:31.720
My name is Pet, and I'm from the Trans Sky, a region in the eastern Cape.

16:31.720 --> 16:33.280
I'm a causeer.

16:33.280 --> 16:38.680
The Koi Koi and sand tribes are part of my tribe, and that's where the name causeer comes

16:38.680 --> 16:39.680
from.

16:39.680 --> 16:46.680
I speak causeer, a language full of clicks because of the influence of Koi and sand words.

16:46.680 --> 16:51.200
I laugh when foreigners try to speak causeer because it's difficult for them to pronounce

16:51.200 --> 16:52.560
the clicks.

16:52.560 --> 16:58.760
I believe in an evil spirit called the Tokolosh, and I visit a witch doctor when I'm ill.

16:58.760 --> 17:03.200
I believe he can help me more than a traditional doctor.

17:03.200 --> 17:09.080
I'm Fatima, and I live in the Boerkop, a colorful Cape Town neighborhood.

17:09.080 --> 17:14.440
I speak Afrikaans, and English, or a combination of the two.

17:14.440 --> 17:19.920
I'm part of a very small group called the Cape Malay Collettes, where the descendants

17:19.920 --> 17:26.760
of slaves from Indonesia, Mozambique, and Madagascar, and we follow Islam.

17:26.760 --> 17:31.160
We love music, and have developed our own style of music.

17:31.160 --> 17:35.600
You can hear it at the lively Cape Minstrel Carnival in Cape Town.

17:35.600 --> 17:41.000
There, people wear costumes and sing and dance in the streets.

17:41.000 --> 17:42.000
Chapter 4.

17:42.000 --> 17:45.280
The Leafs, myths, and legends.

17:45.280 --> 17:50.160
Magic and superstition are an important part of South African culture.

17:50.160 --> 17:55.280
Here are 4 widely held beliefs, which still exist today.

17:55.280 --> 17:57.040
Witch doctors.

17:57.040 --> 18:01.440
The belief in witch doctors is very strong in South Africa.

18:01.440 --> 18:08.800
In fact, about 60% of South Africans visit a witch doctor when they are ill or have problems.

18:08.800 --> 18:14.800
There are 8 times more traditional healers than medical doctors in South Africa.

18:14.800 --> 18:18.160
Witch doctors can be men or women.

18:18.160 --> 18:24.040
Some witch doctors perform spiritual healing by getting advice from their ancestors.

18:24.040 --> 18:28.240
They do this in a ceremony called Throwing the Bones.

18:28.240 --> 18:35.160
They throw bones, animal bones, shells or stones, and interpret their ancestors' messages

18:35.160 --> 18:37.880
from the way the bones fall.

18:37.880 --> 18:43.880
Many witch doctors use medicine called mutti, the Zulu word for tree.

18:43.880 --> 18:51.400
This is made from natural products to cure illnesses or even to help a person find love.

18:51.400 --> 18:56.920
In Johannesburg, there are mutti markets that sell strange objects for use and traditional

18:56.920 --> 18:57.920
healing.

18:57.920 --> 19:03.320
Mutti can contain ingredients like dried animal parts.

19:03.320 --> 19:05.080
The Rain Queen.

19:05.080 --> 19:11.160
The Balobedu people of the Limpopo province believe that the success of their agriculture

19:11.160 --> 19:14.800
depends on a woman called the Rain Queen.

19:14.800 --> 19:20.240
They believe that this mysterious woman has special powers to control the clouds and

19:20.240 --> 19:21.960
rainfall.

19:21.960 --> 19:28.040
In November, the annual rain-making ceremony takes place at the Rain Queen's Royal Palace

19:28.040 --> 19:30.760
in Kettlerkorn village.

19:30.760 --> 19:36.000
People believe that she can bring the rain for agriculture through rituals and by asking

19:36.000 --> 19:39.040
her divine ancestors for help.

19:39.040 --> 19:45.800
She has to provide rain for 150 villages and her people fear and respect her.

19:45.800 --> 19:54.080
Her own gardens are green and have dense vegetation and rare trees as a symbol of her powers.

19:54.080 --> 20:00.440
The Rain Queen has many distinguished servants, all of them from villages all over the Balobedu

20:00.440 --> 20:02.240
kingdom.

20:02.240 --> 20:06.360
They usually come from the houses of the village chiefs.

20:06.360 --> 20:12.240
The Rain Queen is not permitted to get married, but she can have children with honorable men

20:12.240 --> 20:16.000
and these men will provide good successors.

20:16.000 --> 20:21.600
According to custom, the Rain Queen can only communicate with her people through her male

20:21.600 --> 20:23.600
counsellors.

20:23.600 --> 20:30.040
The last Queen, Makobo constant Mujaji, was the sixth and youngest Rain Queen in the history

20:30.040 --> 20:38.160
of the Balobedu, but she died on the 12th of June 2005 at the age of 27.

20:38.160 --> 20:43.480
She left a baby daughter, but the little girl was too young to take the throne.

20:43.480 --> 20:47.280
This usually passes from mother to the eldest daughter.

20:47.280 --> 20:55.640
A Rain Queen's death is supposed to bring natural disasters such as drought, famine and disease.

20:55.640 --> 21:00.440
The Tokolosh In black folklore, many people are frightened

21:00.440 --> 21:05.000
of a mischievous evil spirit called the Tokolosh.

21:05.000 --> 21:10.240
This creature takes many forms but always has a stone in its mouth.

21:10.240 --> 21:13.960
The stone makes it invisible.

21:13.960 --> 21:19.080
According to legend, the only way to keep the Tokolosh away at night is to put something

21:19.080 --> 21:23.880
like a brick or a paint can under each leg of your bed.

21:23.880 --> 21:29.120
Because of this, many Africans raise their beds off the ground so the Tokolosh can't

21:29.120 --> 21:31.360
reach them.

21:31.360 --> 21:37.080
People believe one of the Tokolosh's favourite hobbies is stealing milk from cows.

21:37.080 --> 21:42.480
If the farmer wants to catch the Tokolosh, he gets help from a witch doctor.

21:42.480 --> 21:49.760
The witch doctor makes mutti and after the Tokolosh touches this potion, it becomes visible.

21:49.760 --> 21:53.520
The witch doctor can then kill it.

21:53.520 --> 21:59.520
The legend of Jan Fan Honks During the summer months when the southeast

21:59.520 --> 22:06.160
wind blows, Cape Town's most famous tourist attraction, Table Mountain, is covered with

22:06.160 --> 22:11.440
a white cloud which some people call a tablecloth.

22:11.440 --> 22:17.160
According to an ancient myth, this tablecloth was created by a smoking contest between the

22:17.160 --> 22:22.960
devil and a Dutch pirate called Captain Jan Fan Honks.

22:22.960 --> 22:29.360
Jan Fan Honks lived at the foot of Table Mountain and was a heavy pipe smoker.

22:29.360 --> 22:35.600
Every day he climbed the mountain and sat in his favourite place to smoke.

22:35.600 --> 22:41.640
One day the old pirate was surprised to see a stranger sitting in his place dressed in

22:41.640 --> 22:43.200
black.

22:43.200 --> 22:48.480
The stranger wore a large hat and it almost covered his face.

22:48.480 --> 22:54.960
Jan Honks was astonished when the man greeted him by name and asked for some tobacco.

22:54.960 --> 22:57.880
Fan Honks boasted about his tobacco.

22:57.880 --> 23:03.200
"'Only I can smoke such a large quantity of it,' he said.

23:03.200 --> 23:05.400
Nonsense,' replied the stranger.

23:05.400 --> 23:12.360
"'I can easily smoke as much if not more than you old pirate.'

23:12.360 --> 23:16.840
Overly, Fan Honks challenged him to a smoking contest.

23:16.840 --> 23:21.920
Soon huge clouds of smoke poured from the top of Table Mountain.

23:21.920 --> 23:25.480
The contest continued all day long.

23:25.480 --> 23:33.000
Finally, unable to continue the stranger leaned forward and his hat fell from his head.

23:33.000 --> 23:37.000
It was the devil himself and he was furious.

23:37.800 --> 23:42.800
"'I beat you in the contest devil,' shouted Fan Honks.

23:42.800 --> 23:48.200
Suddenly there was a flash of lightning and Fan Honks and the stranger disappeared into

23:48.200 --> 23:50.200
the smoke.

23:50.200 --> 23:56.520
According to legend, the cloud of tobacco smoke they left behind became Cape Town's famous

23:56.520 --> 23:57.880
tablecloth.

23:57.880 --> 24:01.880
Chapter 5 Places of Interest

24:01.880 --> 24:08.520
The Republic of South Africa is situated at the most southern point of the African continent.

24:08.520 --> 24:13.280
It covers an area of over a million square kilometers.

24:13.280 --> 24:22.320
It has frontiers with Botswana, Namibia, Mozambique, Swaziland, La Soto and Zimbabwe.

24:22.320 --> 24:28.360
The main cities are Johannesburg, Cape Town, Durban and Pretoria.

24:28.360 --> 24:35.280
South Africa is rich in natural resources and is the world's largest producer of gold,

24:35.280 --> 24:40.080
diamonds, platinum, coal and other minerals.

24:40.080 --> 24:47.080
South Africa has got nine different provinces and a very varied landscape including deserts,

24:47.080 --> 24:50.680
mountains and subtropical forests.

24:50.680 --> 24:56.080
There are so many places of interest that it is impossible to cover each province.

24:56.080 --> 24:58.880
Let's look at some of them.

24:58.880 --> 25:05.600
In the western Cape you can find white sandy beaches, forests with ancient trees, nature

25:05.600 --> 25:09.080
reserves, vineyards and mountains.

25:09.080 --> 25:13.760
You can watch whales and dolphins or swim with penguins.

25:13.760 --> 25:19.160
You can even go down to the bottom of the ocean in a cage and observe the great white

25:19.160 --> 25:21.200
sharks.

25:21.200 --> 25:26.640
The sharks sometimes try to eat the metal of the cage but it doesn't taste good so

25:26.640 --> 25:32.200
visitors don't have to worry about becoming a shark's next meal.

25:32.200 --> 25:35.880
The capital of this province is Cape Town.

25:35.880 --> 25:41.440
Many visitors to Cape Town take a boat trip to Robin Island and stand in Nelson Mandela's

25:41.440 --> 25:47.240
prison cell or ride in the cable car to the top of Table Mountain.

25:47.240 --> 25:52.440
The northern Cape is called the Jewel of South Africa because people have found diamonds

25:52.440 --> 25:54.080
there.

25:54.080 --> 25:57.280
But these aren't the province's only jewels.

25:57.280 --> 26:01.000
It is also home to a number of national parks.

26:01.000 --> 26:06.760
The Orange River, South Africa's longest river, flows through the northern Cape.

26:06.760 --> 26:14.360
At the Agrobis Falls the thundering water cascades down from a height of 56 metres.

26:14.360 --> 26:17.680
The Eastern Cape is a surface paradise.

26:17.680 --> 26:23.840
It is located on the Indian Ocean and has got 800 kilometres of beaches.

26:23.840 --> 26:31.040
If you like wild animals you can see the Big Five, Lion, Cape Buffalo, African Elephant,

26:31.040 --> 26:36.520
Leopard and Black Rhino at one of the province's game reserves.

26:36.520 --> 26:42.680
You can also visit some of the battle sites of the Anglo-Bore War and tour Nelson Mandela's

26:42.680 --> 26:48.000
birthplace, the village of Mvezo in the Transchai.

26:48.000 --> 26:55.520
The Green Garden province of Quazulu-Natal borders Mozambique, Swaziland and Lesotho.

26:55.520 --> 27:04.960
Three cultures, European, Indian and Zulu meet here, surrounded by the magnificent 3,475-metre

27:04.960 --> 27:08.720
high Drakensberg Mountains.

27:08.720 --> 27:14.080
You can observe Zulu tribes in their natural environment and stand on the sites of many

27:14.080 --> 27:20.320
battles between Zulu warriors, boar fighters and British soldiers.

27:20.320 --> 27:25.720
The largest city in the province is Durban and this is also the busiest port of South

27:25.720 --> 27:27.720
Africa.

27:27.720 --> 27:34.360
South Africa's smallest province, Chauteng, also known as the Place of Gold is the country's

27:34.360 --> 27:36.440
economic heart.

27:36.440 --> 27:40.200
Johannesburg and Pretoria are situated here.

27:40.200 --> 27:44.800
The gold rush brought people seeking gold to Chauteng.

27:44.800 --> 27:50.520
At first they lived in shanty towns and these later became cities.

27:50.520 --> 27:55.880
The world's largest diamond, the Cullinan Diamond, was discovered in the Cullinan diamond

27:55.880 --> 27:59.120
mine in 1905.

27:59.120 --> 28:07.000
It weighs 3,106 carats and is now part of the British crown jewels.

28:07.000 --> 28:13.120
Another major discovery, a complete 8-man skull and skeleton, dating back more than 3 million

28:13.120 --> 28:17.440
years, was found in the Stirkfontaine caves.

28:17.440 --> 28:23.160
This discovery proved that prehistoric man lived in this area long before the first European

28:23.160 --> 28:24.640
settlers arrived.

28:24.640 --> 28:30.320
Chapter 6 Natural Wonders and Tourist Attractions

28:30.320 --> 28:35.920
Table Mountain National Park Table Mountain National Park is an area of

28:35.920 --> 28:41.240
incredible natural beauty and has got more species of plants than the entire British

28:41.240 --> 28:42.240
Isles.

28:42.240 --> 28:50.080
It is home to two famous sites, Table Mountain and the Cape of Good Hope including Cape Point.

28:50.080 --> 28:54.480
Many different animals live inside the park.

28:54.480 --> 29:00.280
Table Mountain is a significant tourist attraction, with many visitors using the cable car or

29:00.280 --> 29:03.080
walking up to the top.

29:03.080 --> 29:07.840
Around 800,000 people visit Table Mountain annually.

29:07.840 --> 29:13.520
Famous visitors to the top of Table Mountain include King George VI and Queen Elizabeth

29:13.520 --> 29:16.320
II of England.

29:16.320 --> 29:20.800
The view from the top of Table Mountain has been described as one of the most amazing

29:20.800 --> 29:27.040
views in Africa, overlooking Cape Town, Table Bay and Robin Island to the north and

29:27.040 --> 29:31.920
the Atlantic Ocean to the west and south.

29:31.920 --> 29:39.040
Blader River Canyon Situated in the Drakensberg Mountains, the Blader River Canyon is the third

29:39.040 --> 29:41.720
largest canyon in the world.

29:41.720 --> 29:48.800
It has got very unusual rock formations, especially the Borkslug potholes, a series of strange

29:48.800 --> 29:52.720
and spectacular cylindrical sculptures.

29:52.720 --> 29:58.720
According to legend, two million pounds worth of golden diamonds are buried in the canyon.

29:58.720 --> 30:05.440
Apparently, a man named John Holthausen hid the treasure there in 1905.

30:05.440 --> 30:10.800
He went to prison for two and a half years because he stole a horse and carriage.

30:10.800 --> 30:15.960
While he was in prison, he admitted that he and two others hid golden diamonds from the

30:15.960 --> 30:17.920
British.

30:17.920 --> 30:22.820
He knows if this is really true, but treasure hunters are still looking for the missing

30:22.820 --> 30:25.560
millions today.

30:25.560 --> 30:29.440
The Garden Route The Garden Route is one of South Africa's

30:29.440 --> 30:32.440
most popular tourist attractions.

30:32.440 --> 30:37.960
This route extends for 200 kilometres along the Southeastern coast.

30:37.960 --> 30:43.200
The Garden Route offers many activities from searching for wild elephants to travelling

30:43.200 --> 30:45.880
on a steam passenger train.

30:45.880 --> 30:52.200
Two well-known parks, the Wilderness and Tsitsicama National Parks, are situated on

30:52.200 --> 30:54.680
the Garden Route.

30:54.680 --> 30:59.920
Many visitors also travel to the town of Oatthorn to see the Kango Caves.

30:59.920 --> 31:07.960
There, they tore deep inside beautiful caverns and squeezed through extremely narrow tunnels.

31:07.960 --> 31:12.880
Blocran's Bungie The popular sport of bungee jumping started

31:12.880 --> 31:19.400
on Pentecost Island in the South Pacific as a tribal ritual for boys to enter manhood.

31:19.400 --> 31:24.840
Vines were attached to their ankles and tied to two bamboo towers.

31:24.840 --> 31:30.040
Jumpers dived from the highest possible point and stopped close to the ground.

31:30.040 --> 31:34.000
If they succeeded, they were considered a man.

31:34.000 --> 31:40.800
Today, bungee jumping is popular all over the world and the highest jumps are in Nepal,

31:40.800 --> 31:45.720
New Zealand and from Blocran's Bridge in South Africa.

31:45.720 --> 31:52.520
Most people look down from the 216 metre high Blocran's Bridge and tremble with fear.

31:52.520 --> 31:59.800
But those with a passion for adventure enthusiastically bungee jump from the world's highest bridge.

31:59.800 --> 32:05.920
Blocran's bungee jumpers use highly specialised equipment so the risk is very low.

32:05.920 --> 32:11.280
They have to wear a special harness over their entire body because of the extreme height.

32:11.280 --> 32:17.000
So far, there haven't been any accidents, but you may want to say a prayer before you

32:17.000 --> 32:23.160
fly off the bridge and fall down towards the Blocran's River below.

32:23.160 --> 32:30.600
The Palace of the Lost City According to legend, a lost civilisation from North Africa migrated

32:30.600 --> 32:37.520
to Bofututswana in the northwest area of South Africa and built a royal city and magnificent

32:37.520 --> 32:40.680
palace there in the Valley of the Sun.

32:40.680 --> 32:47.440
But one day the city was destroyed by a volcanic eruption and only the palace remained.

32:47.440 --> 32:53.160
The ruins of the palace were discovered next to Sun City, a luxury casino and resort about

32:53.160 --> 32:56.600
a two-hour drive from Johannesburg.

32:56.600 --> 33:02.200
So Kurzner, the owner of the casino, decided to restore the lost city.

33:02.200 --> 33:08.160
He spent millions to create his dream, a combination of the Jungle Book and Indiana Jones and

33:08.160 --> 33:10.000
the Temple of Doom.

33:10.000 --> 33:17.440
The result is the Palace of the Lost City, the world's largest themed resort hotel.

33:17.440 --> 33:24.480
Its 350 rooms are surrounded by an enormous man-made jungle with water cascades, pools

33:24.480 --> 33:27.040
and a massive water park.

33:27.040 --> 33:32.280
The golf course at the Lost City is a worldwide attraction and golfers come from around the

33:32.280 --> 33:35.720
world to take part in competitions there.

33:35.720 --> 33:40.120
But visitors are too frightened to take a ball from the thirteenth hole.

33:40.120 --> 33:41.360
Why?

33:41.360 --> 33:46.080
Because the water around it contains 38 live crocodiles.

33:46.080 --> 33:53.840
Chapter 7 Wildlife in Kruger National Park Kruger National Park

33:53.840 --> 34:00.520
Welcome to Kruger National Park, an enormous game reserve in the Mpoma Langa and Limpopo

34:00.520 --> 34:04.200
provinces in the north of South Africa.

34:04.200 --> 34:11.000
With an area of over 19,000 square kilometres, Kruger Park is one of the largest game reserves

34:11.000 --> 34:12.000
in Africa.

34:12.000 --> 34:15.600
It's even larger than many countries.

34:15.600 --> 34:22.720
The distance from north to south is 360 kilometres, but this journey takes around 10 hours by

34:22.800 --> 34:26.800
car because of animals on the road.

34:26.800 --> 34:32.480
Kruger National Park is named after President Paul Kruger.

34:32.480 --> 34:39.960
After the discovery of gold in the Transval in the 1890s, many people rushed to the area.

34:39.960 --> 34:44.240
Many of them hunted animals for their skin and horns.

34:44.240 --> 34:49.080
President Kruger wanted to protect the animals from the poachers, so he helped to establish

34:49.080 --> 34:51.080
the park.

34:51.080 --> 34:56.240
Kruger National Park opened its gates to visitors in 1927.

34:56.240 --> 35:03.480
Today, more than 1.4 million people from all over the world visit the park every year,

35:03.480 --> 35:08.280
making it one of the top tourist destinations in South Africa.

35:08.280 --> 35:13.880
Visitors can see the greatest variety of wildlife species on the African continent.

35:13.880 --> 35:20.920
They pay a conservation fee to enter the park, and this money helps to protect the wildlife.

35:20.920 --> 35:26.520
Many visitors stay at small hotels inside the park and go on safari, hoping to see the

35:26.520 --> 35:33.080
Big Five, Lion, Buffalo, Elephant, Leopard and Black Rhino.

35:33.080 --> 35:38.880
At Kruger Park, you don't have to imagine a lion standing under a boa-bab tree with the

35:38.880 --> 35:41.440
African sunset in the background.

35:41.440 --> 35:43.800
It's real.

35:43.800 --> 35:48.240
The Big Five When it comes to the Big Five in Africa,

35:48.240 --> 35:51.440
size isn't the most important factor.

35:51.440 --> 35:55.960
What counts is how dangerous it is to hunt the animal on foot.

35:55.960 --> 36:00.240
Lion There are fewer than 21,000 lions in the

36:00.240 --> 36:02.000
whole of Africa.

36:02.000 --> 36:09.600
They are listed as vulnerable by the International Union for Conservation of Nature, IUCN.

36:09.600 --> 36:17.200
A lion can run up to 60 kilometres per hour, and you can hear its roar for 10 kilometres.

36:17.200 --> 36:21.200
Allahari lions are a subspecies in the Northern Cape.

36:21.200 --> 36:25.200
They've got magnificent black mains.

36:25.200 --> 36:29.880
Cape Buffalo Surprisingly, these strong animals are the

36:29.880 --> 36:32.640
most dangerous of the Big Five.

36:32.640 --> 36:37.440
Cape Buffalo have got an exceptional memory, and they never forgive.

36:37.440 --> 36:42.680
If you hurt one, there's a good chance it will hunt you down and kill you.

36:42.680 --> 36:47.320
In Africa, buffalo kill more hunters than any other animal.

36:47.320 --> 36:50.040
Cape Buffalo can even kill lions.

36:50.040 --> 36:58.200
A buffalo is four times as strong as an ox and can easily turn over a car.

36:58.200 --> 37:02.360
African Elephant African elephants are an endangered

37:02.360 --> 37:07.920
species because poachers hunt them for their ivory tusks.

37:07.920 --> 37:11.600
The animal's trunk has got thousands of muscles.

37:11.600 --> 37:18.400
An elephant can kill a lion with its trunk, so it's better not to get too close to one.

37:18.400 --> 37:20.520
Elephants are good ecologists.

37:20.520 --> 37:27.440
They can consume up to 250 kilograms of grass and leaves in one day, but a lot of it is

37:27.440 --> 37:30.480
recycled into the environment.

37:30.480 --> 37:37.560
When the elephant eats seeds, they pass through the animal's digestive system and germinate.

37:37.560 --> 37:41.640
And excrement is also a good fertilizer.

37:41.640 --> 37:45.880
Leopard There are around 1,000 leopards in South

37:45.880 --> 37:47.840
Africa.

37:47.840 --> 37:53.480
Leopards can run up to 60 kilometers per hour, but not for a long time.

37:53.480 --> 37:59.680
They feed mainly on antelope and take their food up into the trees to keep it safe.

37:59.680 --> 38:05.120
Like human fingerprints, each leopard's spots are unique and you'll never find two leopards

38:05.120 --> 38:08.440
with the same spots.

38:08.440 --> 38:13.640
Rhinoceros South Africa is home to almost 5,000 black

38:13.640 --> 38:19.040
rhinos, about 40% of the world's black rhinos.

38:19.040 --> 38:24.280
Rhinos can hear and smell very well, but have poor eyesight.

38:24.280 --> 38:28.640
These heavy animals look very slow, but they're not.

38:28.640 --> 38:32.760
They can run up to 50 kilometers per hour.

38:32.760 --> 38:38.240
The black rhino is the most critically endangered species in South Africa.

38:38.240 --> 38:44.280
In Asia, rhino horn is used in traditional medicine and poachers will risk their lives

38:44.280 --> 38:48.840
to get it for customers in Vietnam and China.

38:48.840 --> 38:53.400
Poachers enter the park illegally and shoot the rhinos with guns.

38:53.400 --> 38:57.480
They cut off the rhinos horn and escape.

38:57.480 --> 39:02.840
The authorities even use helicopters to try and catch the poachers, but are not always

39:02.840 --> 39:04.560
successful.

39:04.560 --> 39:10.000
The worldwide fun for nature is working with South African wildlife authorities in Kruger

39:10.000 --> 39:14.160
National Park to save the rhinos from extinction.

39:14.160 --> 39:15.160
8.

39:15.160 --> 39:21.000
Natural Resources South Africa is the land of gold and diamonds.

39:21.000 --> 39:25.840
But although these natural resources brought a lot of wealth to the country, they also

39:25.840 --> 39:30.200
brought many social and political problems.

39:30.200 --> 39:37.240
Diamonds 15-year-old Erasmus Jakobs didn't know it at the time, but he was going to change

39:37.240 --> 39:40.480
the future of South Africa forever.

39:40.480 --> 39:47.400
It started in 1867 when Erasmus was playing on his farm near Hope Town next to the Orange

39:47.400 --> 39:48.900
River.

39:48.900 --> 39:54.960
He found an interesting stone and used it to play a game called Five Stones.

39:54.960 --> 40:00.280
He then gave the stone to his neighbor and soon it reached the Civil Commissioner.

40:00.280 --> 40:05.240
I believe it's a diamond, the Commissioner declared.

40:05.240 --> 40:12.280
The diamond became known as the Eureka, the first of many to be discovered in South Africa.

40:12.280 --> 40:19.200
A few years later, more diamonds were found in New Rush, today's Kimberley.

40:19.200 --> 40:25.640
As a result of this, thousands of hopeful people suddenly appeared to dig for diamonds.

40:25.640 --> 40:31.600
This led to the establishment of the Kimberley mine, known today as the Big Hole.

40:31.600 --> 40:35.720
The enormous man-made hole is visible from space.

40:35.720 --> 40:44.120
It is 215 metres deep and 2722 kilograms of diamonds were found there.

40:44.120 --> 40:48.680
The Kimberley mine was closed in 1914.

40:48.680 --> 40:49.880
Gold.

40:49.880 --> 40:57.640
In 1886, pieces of gold were discovered on a farm called Langlachte in the Transvaal.

40:57.640 --> 41:03.160
This led to a further discovery of a gold reef 50 kilometres long.

41:03.160 --> 41:09.120
As a result, people came from near and far in search of the gold and the farm became

41:09.120 --> 41:11.720
a big mining camp.

41:11.720 --> 41:18.040
In time, the tents in the mining camp were replaced with houses, offices and shops.

41:18.040 --> 41:24.000
The noisy streets were filled with oxwagons and horses, but the loudest sound came from

41:24.000 --> 41:26.840
the crushing of rocks in the mines.

41:26.840 --> 41:29.800
You could hear it day and night.

41:29.800 --> 41:36.560
Soon there were a number of mining towns and the area became known as the Vipvauterstrand.

41:36.560 --> 41:41.080
The mining town of Langlachte became Johannesburg.

41:41.080 --> 41:47.760
Then it became the biggest town in the Transvaal and was known as the City of Gold.

41:47.760 --> 41:52.120
South Africa became the biggest gold-producing country in the world.

41:52.120 --> 41:58.400
Rich white men made a lot of money from the gold mines, but the African mine workers suffered

41:58.400 --> 41:59.400
terribly.

41:59.400 --> 42:04.760
Johannesburg certainly wasn't a city of gold for them.

42:04.760 --> 42:06.400
Hallelujah.

42:06.400 --> 42:09.640
Every day I thank the Lord that I'm still alive.

42:09.640 --> 42:15.160
I don't know how we're able to work in the gold mines under such terrible conditions.

42:15.160 --> 42:23.040
The boss hits and kicks us and we aren't allowed to talk, so the time passes very slowly.

42:23.040 --> 42:26.760
The work is hard and the hours are long.

42:26.760 --> 42:28.160
But what can I do?

42:28.160 --> 42:30.680
I need money for my family.

42:30.680 --> 42:37.920
Yesterday, the mine flooded again and my dear friend Simelo was killed.

42:37.920 --> 42:40.000
They rest in peace.

42:40.000 --> 42:43.680
I've developed a skin problem from the dirty water.

42:43.680 --> 42:49.600
The boss gave us all rubber gum boots to protect our feet, but that's only because he doesn't

42:49.600 --> 42:53.160
want to spend money on a drainage system.

42:53.160 --> 42:58.560
The boots don't help very much, but at least we can hit them to send messages to each other

42:58.560 --> 43:00.920
instead of talking.

43:00.920 --> 43:05.480
They also make very good musical instruments.

43:05.480 --> 43:11.040
They can separate us from our families, but they can't take our roots from us.

43:11.040 --> 43:17.400
Africa is in our blood and we'll always have our traditional dances to remember our culture

43:17.400 --> 43:19.680
and give us hope.

43:19.680 --> 43:25.720
Next week some important visitors are coming to the mine and we're going to entertain them.

43:25.720 --> 43:32.160
We'll sing songs about our lives, the bad working conditions and our cruel boss.

43:32.160 --> 43:37.640
Of course the visitors won't understand a word because they don't speak our language.

43:37.640 --> 43:40.200
Chapter 9 – Food

43:40.200 --> 43:45.440
The influence of South Africa's different ethnic groups on local food makes a visit to

43:45.440 --> 43:48.240
a restaurant and interesting experience.

43:48.240 --> 43:53.800
Together, these cultural groups give the country its rainbow menu.

43:53.800 --> 43:59.680
The Bantu, as the blacks were known then, taught the early settlers how to grow vegetables

43:59.680 --> 44:03.400
and introduce them to modern agriculture.

44:03.400 --> 44:10.720
The Zulu people introduced the settlers to Mili Mule, a soft cereal made from cornmeal.

44:10.720 --> 44:16.720
The slaves from the east, mostly from Malaysia, brought various spices with them and added

44:16.720 --> 44:20.560
interesting tastes to Dutch and English cooking.

44:20.560 --> 44:25.840
The French Huguenots came to the Cape and transformed part of the land into a fertile

44:25.840 --> 44:30.600
wine growing area called Frenchuk, French Corner.

44:30.600 --> 44:36.040
They planted vineyards there and turned South Africa into one of the world's leading producers

44:36.040 --> 44:37.760
of wine.

44:37.760 --> 44:43.560
The Germans introduced baked goods and cakes and the British brought meat pies.

44:43.560 --> 44:47.440
The Indians worked in the sugarcane fields in Durban.

44:47.440 --> 44:53.440
When their 10-year contracts were over they stayed and Indian cooking became very popular.

44:53.520 --> 44:58.840
Today, Korean rice is a national dish in South Africa.

44:58.840 --> 45:00.800
Barbecues

45:00.800 --> 45:06.680
South Africans are meat lovers and no Sunday meal is complete without a brigh.

45:06.680 --> 45:12.120
This is the South African word for a barbecue and almost every house has got one in its

45:12.120 --> 45:13.960
garden.

45:13.960 --> 45:19.000
This tradition comes from the 17th century when the French Huguenots and Dutch settlers

45:19.000 --> 45:21.640
cook their meat on open fires.

45:21.640 --> 45:27.560
Today, a favourite brigh meat is a German sausage made from beef or pork.

45:27.560 --> 45:33.520
South Africans call it burevos, the African word for farmer's sausage.

45:33.520 --> 45:34.920
Bunny chow

45:34.920 --> 45:41.440
In Durban, you can see street vendors selling some strange-looking bread wrapped in newspaper.

45:41.440 --> 45:48.760
Don't worry, bunny chow is a popular dish made with Indian curry, not baby rabbits.

45:48.840 --> 45:54.640
A hole is made in a quarter, half or whole loaf of white bread and it is then filled

45:54.640 --> 45:58.840
with beef, chicken, lamb or bean curry.

45:58.840 --> 46:04.640
The sauce from the meat is absorbed by the bread, giving it a delicious taste.

46:04.640 --> 46:10.480
The origin of bunny chow isn't clear, but many believe Indian merchants first served

46:10.480 --> 46:13.000
it in a Durban restaurant.

46:13.000 --> 46:17.560
Under apartheid, certain cafes were only open to whites.

46:17.560 --> 46:23.720
The solution was to serve Indian plantation workers through back windows, but the traditional

46:23.720 --> 46:29.960
Indian food was not easy to serve as fast food, so the cafe owners used bread filled

46:29.960 --> 46:32.360
with curry instead.

46:32.360 --> 46:38.000
A funny bunny is made from the middle of the loaf, so there's no hard bit at the bottom.

46:38.000 --> 46:43.960
You have to hold it firmly, or you'll soon find out why it's called a funny bunny.

46:43.960 --> 46:48.320
Biltong Biltong is dried meat and South Africans

46:48.320 --> 46:49.720
love it.

46:49.720 --> 46:54.160
There are different types like beef and ostrich biltong.

46:54.160 --> 46:56.520
Where does biltong come from?

46:56.520 --> 47:01.080
After a hunt, the sand tribe took the meat and cut it into pieces.

47:01.080 --> 47:05.680
They hung it in the sun to dry for up to two weeks, so they would have meat when they

47:05.680 --> 47:07.760
really needed it.

47:07.760 --> 47:13.000
The Dutch also ate a kind of dried meat, but it was made a bit differently.

47:13.000 --> 47:16.320
They added spices and vinegar to preserve it.

47:16.320 --> 47:20.360
The boars liked this idea and started to copy it.

47:20.360 --> 47:25.200
If you haven't tasted biltong, you haven't lived.

47:25.200 --> 47:29.800
Mapani Worms Now you know about the Big Five, but have

47:29.800 --> 47:32.280
you heard of the Big Twelve?

47:32.280 --> 47:35.880
This refers to twelve African insects.

47:35.880 --> 47:42.040
The Mapani Worm, the green and blue caterpillar of the Emperor Moth, is one of these.

47:42.040 --> 47:48.360
It feeds mainly on the leaves of the Mapani tree, and that's the reason for its name.

47:48.360 --> 47:54.360
This fascinating little worm is a local delicacy for people in the northern parts of South Africa

47:54.360 --> 47:57.080
and is served in many restaurants.

47:57.080 --> 48:04.000
In local markets, you can see large bags of sun-dried Mapani worms hanging in the shops.

48:04.000 --> 48:06.240
How are the worms cooked?

48:06.240 --> 48:12.960
Then and children pick the caterpillars by hand and then extract their green insides.

48:12.960 --> 48:17.240
Then they boil the worms and put them in the sun to dry.

48:17.240 --> 48:23.520
You can eat them fried or grilled, or even cook them in a pot with onions and tomatoes.

48:23.520 --> 48:28.400
Some people like them dried and crunchy like potato crisps.

48:28.400 --> 48:33.680
Although not for the faint-hearted, a dish of Mapani worms is a great substitute for

48:33.680 --> 48:39.200
a steak because they contain three times more protein than beef.

48:39.200 --> 48:45.760
Fifteen worms a day give you all the calcium, iron and vitamin B2 you need.

48:45.760 --> 48:50.400
Just make sure they're the biggest fattest ones with the most protein.

48:50.400 --> 48:51.760
Chapter 10.

48:51.760 --> 48:52.720
Art.

48:52.720 --> 48:58.400
From the street markets to the townships and cities, art is all around.

48:58.560 --> 49:04.200
You can see it in the traditional African masks, the colourful beaded jewellery and

49:04.200 --> 49:07.040
the incredible township art.

49:07.040 --> 49:13.600
South African art comes in many different forms, but every piece has got one thing in common.

49:13.600 --> 49:16.360
It tells a story.

49:16.360 --> 49:22.240
Beading is a very popular art form in South Africa and you can see amazing beaded wire

49:22.240 --> 49:24.600
animals everywhere.

49:24.600 --> 49:30.640
These are mainly made by Zimbabwean immigrants and sold at the side of the road.

49:30.640 --> 49:35.800
Many of these immigrants were unable to find work and have used their creative skills

49:35.800 --> 49:38.960
to start their own roadside business.

49:38.960 --> 49:42.320
You can stop and buy one for a small price.

49:42.320 --> 49:48.720
It's not unusual to see tourists leaving South Africa carrying huge beaded giraffes or antelopes

49:48.720 --> 49:52.080
far too big to put in a suitcase.

49:52.080 --> 49:58.240
This woman is from the Underbelly tribe, descendants of Zulu and Coza tribes.

49:58.240 --> 50:02.880
The Underbelly are known for their traditional beadwork.

50:02.880 --> 50:08.720
Beaded clothes and jewellery are worn at ceremonies and are used to decorate things.

50:08.720 --> 50:13.000
As you can see, the woman is wearing a lot of beadwork.

50:13.000 --> 50:19.920
It's a sign of her status and you can be sure she sat for hours making all those clothes.

50:19.920 --> 50:26.560
She takes one bead at a time carefully choosing the colours and can use as many as 300,000

50:26.560 --> 50:32.280
beads to produce a unique piece of art telling the history of the Underbelly in pictures

50:32.280 --> 50:34.120
and symbols.

50:34.120 --> 50:39.400
When an Underbelly woman gets married, she often works for two to three years on a piece

50:39.400 --> 50:43.120
of beadwork for her future husband's parents.

50:43.120 --> 50:49.880
She knows the quality of her work is important if she wants to be accepted into the family.

50:49.880 --> 50:56.840
The general clothes are also important because the Underbelly believe in life after death.

50:56.840 --> 51:02.280
Over the years, they have incorporated materials and symbols from Western civilisation into

51:02.280 --> 51:04.080
their art.

51:04.080 --> 51:09.520
Many people consider it the most impressive beadwork in the world.

51:09.520 --> 51:15.080
Masks are a very popular souvenir item in South Africa and sold in most fairs.

51:15.160 --> 51:21.720
However, they are more representative of the rest of Africa than South Africa.

51:21.720 --> 51:26.720
Masks represent the spirit of an ancestor or god and they were worn in ceremonies like

51:26.720 --> 51:30.720
crop harvesting, weddings and initiations.

51:30.720 --> 51:36.680
As early as the Stone Age, Africa masks were worn in religious ceremonies, celebrations

51:36.680 --> 51:39.080
and coming of age rights.

51:39.080 --> 51:43.440
These included praying, dancing and singing.

51:43.440 --> 51:49.080
Before a wooden mask was made, the mask maker purified himself and prayed for advice and

51:49.080 --> 51:51.520
help from his ancestors.

51:51.520 --> 51:55.400
He also offered a sacrifice to the tree's god.

51:55.400 --> 51:59.560
When the tree was cut down, it was left for a couple of days.

51:59.560 --> 52:03.520
This let the tree's spirits find a new resting place.

52:03.520 --> 52:08.960
Only after that, the masks were created from the wood of the tree.

52:08.960 --> 52:14.960
Today, Africa masks are made of exotic woods, animal skin or even metal.

52:14.960 --> 52:20.080
They are now considered to be valuable pieces of art and are desired by collectors for the

52:20.080 --> 52:23.000
historic and cultural value.

52:23.000 --> 52:28.880
You can see Africa masks in nearly all art museums throughout the world.

52:28.880 --> 52:33.160
D'Amelie Fennie is one of South Africa's famous artists.

52:33.160 --> 52:39.800
He was born in the Western Cape in 1942 and became known for township art.

52:39.800 --> 52:46.040
This kind of art actually developed in the 1920s but in those days it was called struggle

52:46.040 --> 52:47.840
or resistance art.

52:47.840 --> 52:53.960
At that time, the laws of apartheid forced non-Europeans to live in townships.

52:53.960 --> 52:59.440
The conditions there were terrible and African artists started to show how they felt about

52:59.440 --> 53:03.120
apartheid with colorful paintings.

53:03.120 --> 53:07.960
There was a lot of poverty in the townships and oil paints were too expensive for many

53:07.960 --> 53:11.440
of the artists, so they improvised.

53:11.440 --> 53:15.520
This led to the birth of new township art genres.

53:15.520 --> 53:22.040
D'Amelie often drew on the back of old envelopes using nothing but a ballpoint pen.

53:22.040 --> 53:25.720
That's how he started his career as an artist.

53:25.720 --> 53:30.280
When apartheid ended, township art started to change.

53:30.280 --> 53:36.160
In the past, it reflected a country filled with desperate people and no hope.

53:36.160 --> 53:41.720
But artists in the New South Africa have developed their own unique form of township art.

53:41.720 --> 53:45.560
It's bright, colorful and diverse.

53:45.560 --> 53:51.720
They use all kinds of materials to create their art, recycle plastic bags, all parts

53:51.720 --> 53:58.600
of bicycles, dried tea bags, soft drink cans and many other discarded treasures.

53:58.600 --> 54:01.520
Chapter 11 – Sport

54:01.520 --> 54:06.920
If you want to start a conversation with a South African, you can't go wrong with sport.

54:06.920 --> 54:12.800
South Africans love sport, and once they start to talk, they can't stop.

54:12.800 --> 54:19.240
Although the country has produced some top-class athletes, South Africa hasn't always participated

54:19.240 --> 54:22.200
in international sporting events.

54:22.280 --> 54:29.480
During apartheid, South Africans weren't allowed to play sport internationally for 21 years.

54:29.480 --> 54:35.240
But once Nelson Mandela was set free, the sanctions were removed and South Africa became

54:35.240 --> 54:38.600
a part of the world of global sport again.

54:38.600 --> 54:45.160
Since then, the country has hosted the football, cricket and rugby world cups.

54:45.160 --> 54:46.600
Football

54:46.600 --> 54:52.760
To South Africans, football is more than just a game, it's almost a religion.

54:52.760 --> 54:57.440
It doesn't matter if you're black or white or what language you speak.

54:57.440 --> 55:03.720
Football, or soccer as they call it, is for everybody, even for prisoners.

55:03.720 --> 55:08.280
For a long time, prisoners weren't allowed to play football on Robin Island, so they

55:08.280 --> 55:12.840
made their own balls and played in their cells in secret.

55:12.920 --> 55:20.120
Finally, in 1965, the situation changed and prisoners were permitted to play football.

55:20.120 --> 55:26.320
The following year, five political prisoners formed the Makana Football Association and

55:26.320 --> 55:28.880
organized a league on the island.

55:28.880 --> 55:32.680
They proved that football wins over politics.

55:32.680 --> 55:38.200
Today, most of the players in South Africa's national team are black and the name of the

55:38.200 --> 55:43.000
team is Baffana Baffana, meaning the boys the boys.

55:43.000 --> 55:46.760
A local football game is a memorable experience.

55:46.760 --> 55:51.960
It sounds like there are elephants in the stadium, but it's just South African fans

55:51.960 --> 55:57.400
blowing on their vuvuzellas, long colourful plastic horns.

55:57.400 --> 55:58.680
Cricket

55:58.680 --> 56:02.680
Cricket is South Africa's second most popular sport.

56:02.680 --> 56:06.480
The Proteas is the name of the country's national team.

56:06.480 --> 56:10.320
The Protea is the national flower of South Africa.

56:10.320 --> 56:16.320
In the past, mostly English-speaking whites and Indian South Africans play cricket, but

56:16.320 --> 56:19.040
this is slowly changing.

56:19.040 --> 56:24.800
More and more black people are starting to take up cricket at a young age.

56:24.800 --> 56:29.600
The World Cup is the most important international cricket competition.

56:29.600 --> 56:35.560
It takes place every four years and the best cricket players take part.

56:35.560 --> 56:39.240
The first World Cup was in 1975.

56:39.240 --> 56:45.480
In this competition, the West Indies weren't against Australia and took home the trophy.

56:45.480 --> 56:51.240
South Africa weren't allowed to participate in the World Cup until 1992.

56:51.240 --> 56:56.760
But when they did, they showed the world their talent, winning against Australia in the opening

56:56.760 --> 56:58.320
match.

56:58.320 --> 57:03.000
When it comes to international cricket, it's hard to beat South Africa.

57:03.000 --> 57:09.240
They have had the title of best or second best team in the world for many years.

57:09.240 --> 57:10.240
Rugby

57:10.240 --> 57:15.760
The spring box, South Africa's national rugby team, take their name from the country's

57:15.760 --> 57:16.760
national animal.

57:16.760 --> 57:19.360
A kind of deer.

57:19.360 --> 57:25.640
In the past, rugby was considered a white man sport, played by Africanas, but today it's

57:25.640 --> 57:31.040
a game for all, and once again, South Africa competes internationally.

57:31.040 --> 57:34.760
Hi, I'm Francois Pinot.

57:34.760 --> 57:41.640
I was captain of the spring box from 1993 to 1996, and I led them to victory when we hosted

57:41.640 --> 57:45.480
the Rugby World Cup in 1995.

57:45.480 --> 57:51.200
Before that, Australia never lost a single game, but we beat them and went on to win

57:51.200 --> 57:55.960
against the All Blacks, New Zealand, in the final.

57:55.960 --> 58:00.880
We took the trophy by three points, and it was one of the most memorable moments in

58:00.880 --> 58:02.800
history.

58:02.800 --> 58:08.200
After the match, there was a ceremony, and of course, Nelson Mandela attended.

58:08.200 --> 58:12.880
He was wearing my number six shirt, and he embraced me.

58:12.880 --> 58:17.760
In that one moment, 400 years of suffering disappeared.

58:17.760 --> 58:20.800
It shows you the power of sport.

58:20.800 --> 58:25.600
I felt so proud to be South African.

58:25.600 --> 58:32.440
The Rugby Championship, once known as the Tri-Nations, is another important competition.

58:32.440 --> 58:38.040
The winning team is known as the best international team in the Southern Hemisphere.

58:38.040 --> 58:46.240
From 1996 to 2011, South Africa, Australia and New Zealand competed in this event.

58:46.240 --> 58:51.440
These three countries have won six out of the seven World Cups, so it is considered an

58:51.440 --> 58:54.680
honour to win the Tri-Nations.

58:54.680 --> 59:00.160
In 2012, Argentina were also included in this championship.

59:00.160 --> 59:06.720
Chapter 12, South Africa Today, The Flag of South Africa

59:06.720 --> 59:14.000
The current flag of the Republic of South Africa was adopted on 27 April 1994, after

59:14.000 --> 59:16.920
Nelson Mandela was elected president.

59:16.920 --> 59:20.520
It replaced the old flag from 1928.

59:20.520 --> 59:28.120
The new national flag, designed by Frederick Brownell, was chosen to represent the new democracy.

59:28.120 --> 59:32.280
The only symbolism in the flag is the Y shape.

59:32.280 --> 59:38.200
Some say this represents the uniting of different elements within South African society and moving

59:38.200 --> 59:41.000
forward in unity.

59:41.000 --> 59:47.480
Three of the colours, black, green and yellow, are in the flag of the African National Congress.

59:47.480 --> 59:53.360
The other three, red, white and blue, are used in the old flag of the Transvaal, the

59:53.360 --> 59:57.400
flag of the Netherlands and the flag of the United Kingdom.

59:57.400 --> 01:00:02.680
White and blue were also found in the old flag of South Africa.

01:00:02.680 --> 01:00:07.720
Crime Crime is an enormous problem in South Africa today.

01:00:07.720 --> 01:00:11.640
The black and white middle-class communities live in fear.

01:00:11.640 --> 01:00:17.320
Their houses are protected by high walls with electric fencing, guard dogs, bars on

01:00:17.320 --> 01:00:20.320
the window and alarm systems.

01:00:20.320 --> 01:00:23.120
Unemployment levels are very high.

01:00:23.120 --> 01:00:28.880
Because of this, criminal behaviour has become normal for many young South Africans and approximately

01:00:28.880 --> 01:00:33.960
13,000 children are arrested every month for crime.

01:00:33.960 --> 01:00:39.400
There are around 43 murders a day per 100,000 people.

01:00:39.400 --> 01:00:44.360
Most victims are the owners of expensive cars and elegant houses.

01:00:44.360 --> 01:00:50.520
In 8 out of 10 residential robberies, domestic workers, gardeners and former employees are

01:00:50.520 --> 01:00:52.920
involved in the planning.

01:00:52.920 --> 01:00:57.720
Hunger and poverty is the motive of 35% of robbers.

01:00:57.720 --> 01:01:05.160
Most robbers rob 103 times over a period of 7 years before they are caught.

01:01:05.160 --> 01:01:09.080
Poverty As you leave Johannesburg or Cape Town,

01:01:09.080 --> 01:01:15.480
you can't ignore the slums at the borders of the cities and in rural areas.

01:01:15.480 --> 01:01:21.040
Here you can find around half a million people living in very poor conditions.

01:01:21.040 --> 01:01:24.440
Many still live without electricity and water.

01:01:24.440 --> 01:01:29.080
A short drive around the suburbs of Johannesburg will reveal the truth.

01:01:29.080 --> 01:01:33.360
There is still a very clear division between rich and poor.

01:01:33.360 --> 01:01:41.120
This is still causing problems in South Africa, almost 20 years after the end of apartheid.

01:01:41.120 --> 01:01:45.760
AIDS AIDS is one of South Africa's greatest problems.

01:01:45.760 --> 01:01:51.880
More than 5.6 million people in South Africa today are HIV positive.

01:01:51.880 --> 01:01:55.440
That's about 10% of the total population.

01:01:55.440 --> 01:02:01.120
It has got the highest number of HIV AIDS cases in the world.

01:02:01.120 --> 01:02:07.040
South Africa is trying to reduce the number of new HIV infections and has expanded treatment

01:02:07.040 --> 01:02:11.880
for people living with HIV, especially pregnant women.

01:02:11.880 --> 01:02:17.680
Last year more than 260,000 people with AIDS died.

01:02:17.680 --> 01:02:22.880
South Africa Forecast for the future Mandela's dream

01:02:22.880 --> 01:02:28.440
Mandela's dream was to create a country free of poverty and social inequality.

01:02:28.440 --> 01:02:31.840
It is dream is far from the reality.

01:02:31.840 --> 01:02:36.880
Modern South Africa has a long way to go to achieve Mandela's dream.

01:02:36.880 --> 01:02:44.520
Although a truly democratic South Africa seems far away, with careful planning, it can happen.

01:02:44.520 --> 01:02:51.240
The first step is to reduce unemployment and to increase the standard of education for black pupils.

01:02:51.240 --> 01:02:57.320
An extra 12 million pupils in public schools now have the right to basic education and in

01:02:57.320 --> 01:03:03.480
higher education, financial help for studies is available for poor students.

01:03:03.480 --> 01:03:09.040
Better social conditions and health education will help reduce the number of AIDS victims

01:03:09.040 --> 01:03:12.480
and create a healthier population.

01:03:12.480 --> 01:03:20.200
Since April 2010, 500,000 new patients have been given treatment and HIV AIDS deaths have

01:03:20.200 --> 01:03:25.960
been reduced by 50% to fewer than 270,000.

01:03:25.960 --> 01:03:31.640
The transmission of HIV from mother to child in South Africa has begun to decrease in recent

01:03:31.640 --> 01:03:38.320
years from 8% in 2010 to 2.7% in 2013.

01:03:38.320 --> 01:03:44.200
Finally, with the help of foreign investors, the economy will grow.

01:03:44.200 --> 01:03:50.800
If these steps are taken, maybe 20 years from now, the dream of a democratic South Africa

01:03:50.800 --> 01:03:57.080
will replace today's reality and Nelson Mandela's hopes and dreams will come true.

01:03:57.080 --> 01:04:04.400
Page 64 Cross-curricular Focus South African Films

01:04:04.400 --> 01:04:12.320
Invictus The 2009 film Invictus, based on a true story,

01:04:12.320 --> 01:04:19.760
is a drama about the events surrounding the 1995 Rugby World Cup in South Africa.

01:04:19.760 --> 01:04:26.680
Directed by Clint Eastwood, this inspiring film starring Morgan Freeman as Nelson Mandela

01:04:26.680 --> 01:04:33.560
and Matt Damon as Springbok rugby captain Francois Pinaire showed how sport could unite

01:04:33.560 --> 01:04:36.000
different people.

01:04:36.000 --> 01:04:39.160
The film is set in 1995.

01:04:39.160 --> 01:04:45.120
Mandela was president of South Africa and apartheid was at an end, but the country was

01:04:45.120 --> 01:04:50.880
in turmoil and there was a lot of hatred between the blacks and the whites.

01:04:50.880 --> 01:04:54.840
South Africa was going to host the Rugby World Cup.

01:04:54.840 --> 01:05:01.400
The blacks hated the South African rugby team because it was dominated by whites, but Mandela

01:05:01.400 --> 01:05:05.840
was determined to change this with the help of Pinaire.

01:05:05.840 --> 01:05:11.720
He persuaded the mainly black South African sports committee to support the spring box

01:05:11.720 --> 01:05:17.840
and met with Pinaire, inspiring the captain to conquer hate with rugby.

01:05:17.840 --> 01:05:24.480
The highly motivated Pinaire worked hard preparing his team for the World Cup and slowly won

01:05:24.480 --> 01:05:28.160
the support of black people around the country.

01:05:28.160 --> 01:05:34.680
By the time the big day arrived, Pinaire proved that rugby could unite a divided nation and

01:05:34.680 --> 01:05:42.360
in the final, the spring box led a more united South Africa to victory over New Zealand.

01:05:42.360 --> 01:05:50.640
Page 66 Cross Curricular Focus Skin

01:05:50.640 --> 01:05:56.840
Skin 2008 was the tragic true story of Sandra Lang.

01:05:56.840 --> 01:06:04.400
Although her parents were white Africanas, Sandra's skin was dark and her hair was curly.

01:06:04.400 --> 01:06:12.480
An unusual situation, but in a country with apartheid, this was a disaster.

01:06:12.480 --> 01:06:17.480
The young Sandra became an outcast because she had dark skin.

01:06:17.480 --> 01:06:26.680
In 1965, at the age of 10, she was classified as coloured and removed from school.

01:06:26.680 --> 01:06:32.800
Sandra's father, Abraham, couldn't accept this and he fought for her to be reclassified

01:06:32.800 --> 01:06:34.480
as white.

01:06:34.480 --> 01:06:41.160
He succeeded, but at that time in South Africa, the colour of your skin dictated your life

01:06:41.160 --> 01:06:46.960
and Sandra was never truly accepted by the white community.

01:06:46.960 --> 01:06:52.760
Sandra felt more comfortable in the company of blacks and Abraham was dismayed when she

01:06:52.760 --> 01:06:57.520
fell in love with a black man named Petrus and married him.

01:06:57.520 --> 01:07:04.360
Abraham disowned Sandra and didn't allow his wife Sanny to communicate with their daughter.

01:07:04.360 --> 01:07:10.040
But Sandra's marriage didn't last because Petrus became physically abusive.

01:07:10.040 --> 01:07:14.440
Sandra took their two children and left.

01:07:14.440 --> 01:07:20.400
When apartheid came to an end, there was renewed interest in Sandra's story.

01:07:20.400 --> 01:07:25.240
She appeared in an interview and Sanny saw her on TV.

01:07:25.240 --> 01:07:29.520
She wrote to Sandra, telling her of her father's death.

01:07:29.520 --> 01:07:37.000
The two were finally reunited after 29 years apart, only a short time before Sanny's death.

